ical","name":"politics","category":"Topic","short_permalink":"http:\/\/www.breakingnews.com\/t\/C","wikipedia_url":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Politics","twitter_username":"breakingpol","slug":"politics","facebookchat":"","image_credit":"Photo: <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Politics\">Wikipedia<\/a>","latitude":null,"active":true,"item_count":52674,"image_width":802,"trend_rank_current":2,"longitude":null,"livevideo":"","description":"<p><b>Politics<\/b> (from Greek:  <i>politikos<\/i>, meaning \"of, for, or relating to citizens\") is the practice and theory of influencing other people on a global, civic or individual level. More narrowly, it refers to achieving and exercising positions of governance  organized control over a human community, particularly a state. Furthermore, politics is the study or practice of the distribution of power and resources within a given community (a hierarchically organized population) as well as the interrelationship(s) between communities. A variety of methods are employed in politics, which include promoting one's own political views among people, negotiation with other political subjects, making laws, and exercising force, including warfare against adversaries. Politics is exercised on a wide range of social levels, from clans and tribes of traditional societies, through modern local governments, companies and institutions up to sovereign states, to the international level.<\/p>\n<p>A political system is a framework which defines acceptable political methods within a given society. History of political thought can be traced back to early antiquity, with seminal works such as Plato's <i>Republic<\/i>, Aristotle's <i>Politics<\/i> and the works of Confucius.<\/p>","image_height":788,"geohash":"","latest_item_date":"2015-03-24T00:39:46.820818"},{"items_resource_uri":"\/api\/v1\/item\/?topics=15","related_topics_uri":"\/api\/v1\/topic\/?related_to=15","id":15,"created_on":"2012-11-28T17:18:48","recent_count":2,"image_url":"http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/a\/a7\/Cyprian_War.jpg","permalink":"http:\/\/www.breakingnews.com\/topic\/war-conflict\/","daily_count":25,"trend_rank_last":17,"muted_by_default":false,"woeid":null,"resource_uri":"\/api\/v1\/topic\/15\/","local_url":"\/topic\/war-conflict\/","placetype":"","links":"","kind":"vertical","name":"war & conflict","category":"Topic","short_permalink":"http:\/\/www.breakingnews.com\/t\/P","wikipedia_url":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/War","twitter_username":null,"slug":"war-conflict","facebookchat":"","image_credit":"Photo: <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/War\">Wikipedia<\/a>","latitude":null,"active":true,"item_count":29522,"image_width":589,"trend_rank_current":17,"longitude":null,"livevideo":"","description":"<p><b>War<\/b> is an organized and often prolonged conflict that is carried out by states or non-state actors. It is generally characterised by extreme violence, social disruption and economic destruction. War should be understood as an actual, intentional and widespread armed conflict between political communities, and therefore is defined as a form of (collective) political violence or intervention. The set of techniques used by a group to carry out war is known as <b>warfare<\/b>. An absence of war is usually called peace.<\/p>\n<p>While some scholars see warfare as an inescapable and integral aspect of human nature, others argue that it is only inevitable under certain socio-cultural or ecological circumstances. For some the practice of war is not linked to any single type of political organization or society. Rather, as discussed by John Keegan in his <i>A History of Warfare<\/i>, war is a universal phenomenon whose form and scope is defined by the society that wages it. Another argument suggests that since there are human societies in which warfare does not exist, humans may not be naturally disposed for warfare, which emerges under particular circumstances.<\/p>\n<p>The deadliest war in history, in terms of the cumulative number of deaths since its start, is the Second World War, with 6085 million deaths, followed by the Mongol conquests. Proportionally speaking, the most destructive war in modern history is the War of the Triple Alliance, which took the lives of over 60% of Paraguay's population, according to Steven Pinker. In 2003, Richard Smalley identified war as the sixth (of ten) biggest problems facing humanity for the next fifty years.<\/p>","image_height":768,"geohash":"","latest_item_date":"2015-03-23T23:42:47.566836"}]},{"push_content":"Photo: Canadian Foreign Minister John Baird and US Secretary of State John Kerry pay tribute at Canada's National War Memorial - @DFATDCanada","shortened_url":"http:\/\/bit.ly\/1wzp9RC","id":458679,"type":"text","author":{"username":"grace.johnson","id":11,"resource_uri":"\/api\/v1\/user\/11\/","email":"grace.johnson@breakingnews.com","last_name":"Johnson","first_name":"Grace","is_staff":false,"full_name":"Grace Johnson"},"permalink":"http:\/\/www.breakingnews.com\/item\/2014\/10\/28\/photo-canadian-foreign-minister-john-baird-and-us","media":{"width":1024,"height":681,"author_name":"DFATD","url":"http:\/\/pbs.twimg.com\/media\/B1DTcDRCQAEo668.jpg","title":".@HonJohnBaird &amp; @JohnKerry Pay Tribute to Memory of Fallen Soldiers at Canadas National War Memorial http:\/\/t.co\/Hn72dYwZlN","id":52859,"thumbnail_url":"http:\/\/pbs.twimg.com\/media\/B1DTcDRCQAEo668.jpg:thumb","thumbnail_width":150,"type":"photo","resource_uri":"","author_url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/DFATDCanada","provider_url":"https:\/\/twitter.com","provider_name":"Twitter","original_url":"http:\/\/twitter.com\/DFATDCanada\/status\/527153636837961728\/photo\/1","html":"","thumbnail_height":150},"url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/DFATDCanada\/status\/527153636837961728\/photo\/1","content":"Photo: Canadian Foreign Minister John Baird and US Secretary of State John Kerry pay tribute at Canada's National War Memorial - @DFATDCanada","date_ap":"